1. c4 c5 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. Nc3 Nc6 { Commonly stated by experts as "mutual zugzwang". There has been lots of debates of what the best move to play by white is. What if Black copies? Can white really prove an advantage with the first move? My recommendation is Nf3. } 5. Nf3! (5. e4?! { My recommendation against the Kings Indian is e4, the Botvinnik setup. From experience, I find the Botvinnik is not effective if Black has not committed either Nf6 or e5. } 5... d6 6. Nge2 e6 7. O-O Nge7 8. d3 O-O 9. Be3 Nd4 { Black is doing well here. No advantage whatsoever for White. }) 5... Nf6 (5... e6 { The Fischer System, in my opinion one of the toughest systems to beat. } 6. d4 { I recommend this line as it sidesteps the center controlling Nge7 + d5 by BLack. } 6... cxd4 (6... Nxd4 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Nb5 Qb6 9. e3 { With pressure on the dark square holes. }) 7. Nb5 d5 8. cxd5 Qa5+ (8... exd5 9. O-O Nge7 10. Nbxd4 { With good play against the isolated d5 pawn }) 9. Nd2 Qxb5 10. dxc6 bxc6 11. a4 Qb6 { Plenty of compensation for the pawn, and likely will win back the pawn on c6 and more! } 12. Nc4 Qb4+ 13. Bd2 Qxc4 14. Rc1) 6. d4 { The best way to avoid symmetry: Opening up the position } 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 { Black cannot easily take advantage of the discovered attack } 8... O-O 9. O-O d6 10. Qd3 { The main line. } 10... a6 (10... Rb8 11. Be3 b6 12. Bd4 Bb7 13. e4 { Again, the very standard Maroczy Bind structure. Play solid, line your rooks on the d and e-files, and slowly play for a squeeze. }) (10... Bf5 11. e4 Be6 12. b3 Rc8 13. Be3 a6 14. Bd4 { Typical Maroczy Bind structure. Very solid. }) 11. Bd2 Bf5 12. e4 Be6 13. b3 Rc8 14. Rac1 { Most of the lines end with some sort of Maroczy Bind hold with c4 and e4. Watch for the pawn break b5 by BLack. Do not rush this position! } *


