1. c4 c5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 { This move order is the only way for Black to break open the center first. Given White moved first, the presence of Black taking initiative first is quite bold. However, White has tricks up his sleeve, ones that break open the center when Black least expects. } 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nc3 Nc7 { The main line to keep a stable center. Ideally, BLack wants to maintain the standard Maroczy Bind center with c5 and e5. } (5... Nxc3 6. bxc3 Nc6 7. Rb1 e5 8. Qa4 Qc7 9. Nf3 { White has a lot of pressure on the queenside from afar. }) 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O e5 8. a3 Be7 (8... f6 9. e3 Be7 10. d4 { A thematic break! Notice Black hasn't castled yet } 10... cxd4 11. exd4 exd4 12. Ne2 d3 (12... Ne6) 13. Nf4 Bf5 14. Nh4 { Eventually the d3 pawn is regained and White's pieces are actively placed with open lines on all sides of the board. }) 9. b4! { Shocking for Black! Since Black has no castled yet, the king runs into some trouble. } 9... cxb4 (9... O-O 10. b5 Nd4 11. Nxe5) (9... f6 10. bxc5 Bxc5 11. e3 O-O 12. d4 exd4 13. Na4 { Typically any break in the center leads to an advantage for the side playing against the Maroczy Bind since now f6 is awkwardly placed. }) 10. axb4 Bxb4 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 (11... Bxc3 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. dxc3) 12. Qa4+ Nc6 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Qxb4 { Better pawn structure and immense long term control on the queenside for white. } *


