1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. e4 d6 6. Nge2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d3 Nh5 { Another somewhat common response which is similar to the plans in the Classical Kings Indian Defense. This move aims for the thematic f5 but also tries to prove that the Nh5 is useful in the attack where it is, instead of retreating back to f6 as soon as f5 is played. } (8... Nd7 9. f4 f5 10. exf5! gxf5 11. Nd5 { Black's Nd7 is very awkward in non-standard Kings Indian setups. exf5 is best now because gxf5 is practically forced. } 11... Nf6 12. fxe5 dxe5 13. Bg5 { The side by side hanging e- and f- pawns will likely act as weaknesses for Black rather than strengths. }) 9. Nd5 f5 10. exf5 Bxf5 (10... gxf5 11. f4) 11. h3 Be6 12. g4 Nf6 13. Bg5 *


