1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. cxd5 Nxd5 4. g3 g6 (4... e5 { Transposes back to the English }) 5. Bg2 { Two main moves for Black: 5. Nxc3 and 5. Nb6 } 5... Nxc3 (5... Nb6 6. d3 Bg7 7. Be3 { Setting up the thematic battery Be3+Qd2 } 7... O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 (8... Re8 9. Bh6 Bh8 10. h4 { h-file is opening up and Black cannot prevent it. } 10... Nc6 11. h5 e5 12. hxg6 hxg6 13. Ne4 { Bg5 is the threat, leading to a great attack. } 13... f6 14. Nf3) 9. Bxc6!? { This move that permanently damages Black's pawn structure scores well in practice. } 9... bxc6 10. Bh6 Nd5 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. h4 h5 13. Nf3 { Black can't easily take advantage of the extra control of the light squares. }) 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Rb1 { Open file, easy target on b7! } 7... c6 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Nd7 10. Qc2 e5 11. d3 Qc7 12. Nd2 Nf6 13. c4 { Play it slow. Knight often hops to a5 to put even more pressure on b7, the base of the pawn chain. Ba3 will complete development } *


