1. c4 e6 { Often the move order played by Queens Gambit Declined (d4 d5 c4 e6) players. However, since this is a pure English repertoire, no transpositions! } 2. e4 d5 (2... c5 { Transposes to a Sicilian. Typically, Sicilian players don't play 1. e6, a French/QGD opening. So psychologically, you would be ahead. } 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Bd3 d5 9. exd5 exd5 10. O-O { This is my recommendation. Quick and easy development. Black's c and d pawns are likely going to be weaknesses in the middlegame and endgame }) 3. exd5 exd5 4. d4 { The specialty of Latvian Grandmaster Normunds Miezis, who has played 200 games in this line! See a few of his games below in this study. } 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 (5... Be7 { The more passive move, which leads to slower play. } 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Be2 dxc4 { Black often plays dxc4 now so the Be2 has to move again. } 8. Bxc4 Bg4 9. O-O Nc6 10. Be3 Bxf3 { Does not win a pawn } 11. Qxf3 Nxd4 12. Qxb7) 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Be2 dxc4 8. Bxc4 { Typical isolated queen pawn position. Keep minor pieces on the board and utilize the e5 square for your knight. Often, you can get a quick kingside attack going. } 8... Re8+ 9. Be3 { White cannot castle yet, but no fear. } 9... Ng4 { A common attempt to stall castling from White. But this does not work tactically for Black. } 10. O-O Nxe3 (10... Rxe3 11. fxe3 Nxe3 12. Bxf7+ Kh8 13. Qb3 Nxf1 14. Qxb4 { White ends up winning in all of these lines due to the tactics against the Black king. }) 11. Bxf7+ Kxf7 12. fxe3 { Discovered checks everywhere, and Qb3+, winning the bishop on b4. } 12... Bxc3 (12... Kg8 13. Qb3+ Be6 14. Qxb4) 13. Ng5+ Ke7 14. Qb3 *


